  "prompt": "Why is the Beatles song (originally from The Music Man) called \u201cTill there was you\u201d and not \u201cTill there were you\u201d?",
  "response": "The grammatical structure of the song title \"Till There Was You\" actually follows a traditional, poetic form of expression. While \"Till There Were You\" might seem more grammatically correct in modern usage, the original lyric uses \"was\" as a stylistic choice that sounds more romantic and singable.\n\nThe song was originally written by Meredith Willson for the musical \"The Music Man\" in 1957, and the Beatles later covered it on their album \"With the Beatles\" in 1963. The use of \"was\" in this context is more about artistic expression and musical flow than strict grammatical rules.\n\nIn the context of the song, \"was\" suggests a sense of discovery or a transformative moment - implying that before this person came into the singer's life, something was missing or incomplete. It's a poetic way of saying that the world or the singer's perception changed with the arrival of this special person.\n\nSo while \"were\" might be technically more correct in standard grammar, \"was\" works better artistically and musically in this context.",
